<HEADLINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO / BRADLEY INMAN; 
</P>
<P>
STATE UNEMPLOYMENT INSURANCE FUND HAS PLENTY FOR RAINY DAYS AHEAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BRADLEY INMAN, BRADLEY INMAN is an Oakland writer specializing in California 
business issues. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At least one part of state government isn't inflicted with a budget ailment. As 
lawmakers grapple with an estimated $4.3-billion state budget deficit, the 
Unemployment Insurance Fund has $5.6 billion in reserves. Financial analysts 
say the plump unemployment kitty should be more than enough to cover the costs 
of a climbing jobless rate. 
</P>
<P>
Mandated by a federal law but administered by the state, the 55-year-old fund 
is responsible for paying out unemployment insurance benefits to workers who 
have lost their jobs. The fund was created in 1935 to protect workers from the 
worst ravages of unemployment and keep money flowing through the economy. 
</P>
<P>
After eight years of strong growth, the California fund has a record high 
balance -- it has nearly doubled in the past five years. 
</P>
<P>
Plus, when the unemployment rate rises, the tax will go up, which shores up the 
fund. The number of people receiving unemployment insurance benefits has 
increased to 386,700 in 1990 from 293,400 in 1989 because of a sharp increase 
in layoffs in the state. A year ago, 721,000 California workers were out of 
work; today, 884,000 are. 
</P>
<P>
On Jan. 1, the ceiling for unemployment insurance benefits will jump to $210 
from $190 a week. In 1992, it will go up to $230. 
</P>
<P>
When lawmakers were negotiating the benefits last year, "the arguments were the 
same," said Carol Ross, research director at the California Taxpayers Assn. in 
Sacramento. "Labor wanted higher benefits and said the fund was too fat, and 
business said reduce the tax and save the surplus for a rainy day." 
</P>
<P>
After the two sides agreed on a new benefits and tax formula, they finally got 
the governor's support with a bill that increased benefits but also tightened 
up who is entitled to unemployment insurance. Nationwide, there is concern that 
the number of jobless collecting unemployment is shrinking. But in California, 
the percentage of unemployed who receive benefits has jumped to 43% today from 
36% in 1984. That could decrease with the new eligibility requirements, 
however. 
</P>
<P>
Beginning Jan. 1, new rules require unemployed workers to have earnings of at 
least $1,250 in any three-month period of their previous jobs. This is up from 
$1,200. It will increase to $1,300 in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
California still has lower unemployment benefits than most other states. Its 
average is $127 a week, which ranks California 37th among all states. The 
highest benefits are paid in Massachusetts, with an average weekly benefit of 
$211. 
</P>
<P>
The unemployment insurance fund is often hailed for its fairness to employers. 
Businesses that have high turnover have a higher tax rate; those that keep 
workers for a long period pay the least. 
</P>
<P>
California businesses pay two unemployment insurance taxes: a 0.8% federal tax 
on the first $7,000 of income for each employee, which covers the costs of 
administering the federal and state unemployment insurance program. A state tax 
covers the cost of benefits and ranges from 0.1% to 5.4% on the first $7,000 of 
taxable income. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing Yields More, Better Jobs 
</P>
<P>
Communities interested in creating more jobs, higher incomes and more sales 
should recruit a big manufacturing plant -- not a supermarket or a computer 
research facility -- a new study by the state Department of Commerce says. 
</P>
<P>
Dubbed "The Economic Benefits of 100 New Jobs," the analysis examines the 
benefits a new business with 100 employees would bring to a community. 
</P>
<P>
The conclusion is that the multiplier effect from 100 manufacturing jobs is 
much greater than the economic spinoff from retail or service industries. 
</P>
<P>
For example, a new supermarket in the San Joaquin Valley that employs 100 
workers would generate 67 more jobs in the community, but a manufacturing 
facility, such as a food processer, would spawn 480 more jobs. Also, food 
processing workers earn 54% higher salaries than retail clerks in the San 
Joaquin Valley. 
</P>
<P>
For those cities that are hungry for tax revenue, however, retail is a better 
option. The food processing plant will generate an estimated $320 million in 
tax revenue, while the supermarket brings in $761 million in tax receipts. 
</P>
<P>
But "if the choice is manufacturing or service jobs, manufacturing is still the 
way to go," said Lance Barnett, chief economist of the Department of Commerce 
in Sacramento. "Manufacturing gives workers a better job ladder to earn more 
and move up," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Despite the drop in manufacturing nationwide, Barnett said, the sector is 
strong in California. In the past 10 years, manufacturing employment rolls grew 
to 2,158,000 from 2,018,000, and the state's share of manufacturing jobs 
nationwide climbed from 8% to 11%. 
</P>
</TEXT>
