<HEADLINE>
<P>
STANDARD TIME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Poor Alex Ferguson, the letter-writer (Oct. 7) who bemoaned the loss of beauty 
and the loss of soul caused by his 2,000-year-old tradition's loss of 
exclusivity. I'd recognize him anywhere. 
</P>
<P>
He's the same man with the same "beauty" and the same "soul" who asks, "What 
about standards?" 
</P>
<P>
Excuse me for not being terribly moved by the tragedy of the loss of form, but 
I for one would rather hear from all those whose backs his precious tradition 
stood on in order to wave its banner -- and I'd rather hear it from them, the 
way they say it, not the way Mr. Ferguson prefers to hear it said in order to 
keep himself cozy. 
</P>
<P>
Standards? Yes. I think it's time we had some. 
</P>
<P>
KATE McFADDEN 
</P>
<P>
ARCADIA 
</P>
</TEXT>
