</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 14; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
98 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHARACTER TRADEMARKS BY JOHN MENDENHALL (CHRONICLE BOOKS: $14.95). 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Charles Solomon 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This delightful anthology of characters used as logos by American businesses 
includes both the famous (Speedy Alka-Seltzer, Poppin' Fresh, The Jolly Green 
Giant) and the infamous, (the bizarre Chicken Boy who watches over downtown 
L.A.). The styles of the various characters suggest the changes in advertising 
graphics -- and taste -- that occurred over the decades: The original Aunt 
Jemima was an ugly black stereotype, who bears only scant resemblance to the 
pretty, lighter-skinned woman on modern packages. A treasure trove for 
illustrators and graphic designers. Charles Solomon 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Name these company logos! . . . answers at bottom: Clockwise from top 
